<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-05-31T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-05-31T02:00:00-05:00" n="585" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d585">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.003/106: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-05-31T15:00:00+08:00">May 31, 1929—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 31—7:48 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>435. Following from the Minister at Nanking:</p>
                        <p>May 30, 9 p.m. Today the Japanese Minister informed several of his
                            colleagues, myself included, that he had received a confidential
                            intimation from a “fairly authoritative source” in the Chinese
                            Government <pb facs="0717" n="573" xml:id="pg_573"/> of its intention to
                            declare the abolition next January 1 of all extraterritorial rights. The
                            Belgian Minister said he, too, had received a somewhat less definite
                            intimation from the Minister for Foreign Affairs to the same effect.</p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
